\begin{abstract}
In recent years, the increase in cyberattacks on corporate networks has driven the use of machine learning methods to identify intrusions. In this study, we analyze the performance of two models: Random Forest (RF) and Deep Neural Network (DNN)—applied to the detection of malicious traffic using the dataset CSE-CIC-IDS2018. We followed the CRISP-DM methodology, which ranged from data cleaning and the selection of key features to balancing and class clustering to address the imbalance in the dataset. We tested both models in two training rounds and evaluated them using metrics such as accuracy, recall, and F1-score. In the end, Random Forest stood out with an overall accuracy of 94.55\%, offering a more robust balance across the different classes. On the other hand, the DNN, thanks to the weights assigned to the classes, significantly improved at detecting less common attacks—reaching a recall of 96\% for Web Attacks—but this came at the cost of slightly lowering the overall accuracy. This highlights the typical trade-off between broad accuracy and greater sensitivity toward minority classes.
\keywords{Intrusion Detection  \and Random Forest \and Deep Neural Network \and CSE-CIC-IDS2018 \and Network Traffic}
\end{abstract}
