\section{Introduction}
In recent years, interest in artificial intelligence, data processing, and the use of corporate networks for access control and management has grown steadily [10]. As technology has evolved, so have intrusions and attacks. These unauthorized intrusions through network traffic compromise core security properties — confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data [23]. This makes intrusion detection models a critical research topic; a sufficiently accurate model can prevent financial losses caused by unauthorized access, or reputational damage resulting from availability attacks on a service.

Previous studies on intrusion classification models use the CSE-CIC-IDS2018 dataset, but focus narrowly on DDoS and DoS attacks [5, 7], or on binary classification [22]. The performance of minority classes within Random Forest (RF) and Deep Neural Network (DNN) models remains largely unexplored. This dataset simulates a real-world environment to capture attack data, producing evidence of network traffic patterns that supports the development of Intrusion Detection Systems (IDS).

This study evaluates the accuracy of RF and DNN in detecting intrusions based on network traffic using the CSE-CIC-IDS2018 dataset. Results are compared across two iterations, with both models focused on detecting grouped dataset classes.

The paper is structured as follows: a theoretical framework, a materials and methods section, a results section, a discussion section, and a conclusions section.

\subsection{Intrusion Detection System (IDS)}
An Intrusion Detection System (IDS) is a fundamental instrument for the security and protection of Internet of Things (IoT) devices. It is designed to identify both external and internal attacks on networks or computer systems, often outperforming traditional firewalls [1, 2]. Recent integration of advanced techniques such as Federated Learning and Explainable Artificial Intelligence (XAI) has improved transparency and privacy in these systems, addressing key limitations of conventional Deep Learning (DL) approaches [12].
\\
At its core, an IDS collects and processes data to generate alerts through a dedicated mechanism; those alerts are then forwarded to a network analyst for thorough investigation [3, 17].
IDS are classified into four methods: Signature-Based IDS (SIDS), Anomaly-Based IDS (AIDS), Specification-Based IDS (SpIDS), and Hybrid IDS (HyIDS). In practice, however, two detection approaches dominate: signature-based and anomaly-based methods [1].
\\
SIDS operates through abuse detection — it matches intrusion signatures against known patterns stored in a database. This yields highly effective and precise detection of known attacks, with low false positive rates, but renders the system ineffective against unknown threats [21]. AIDS, by contrast, is behavior-based detection. It monitors system activity logs and flags deviations from normal behavior, making it capable of detecting unknown, insider, and zero-day attacks — though typically at the cost of higher false positive rates [1, 16].
\\
AIDS are critical precisely because both known and, above all, unknown attack vectors represent a major cybersecurity threat today. These systems work by building a statistical distribution of intrusion patterns through deep analysis of transmitted data, enabling malware identification [1, 15].

\subsection{Taxonomy of Common Attacks in Datasets}
IDS are typically evaluated and trained using datasets containing examples of both benign and malicious traffic, though these datasets are most often imbalanced — with approximately 98\% normal traffic and only 2\% classified as malicious attacks [1, 18]. The following are the attack types most commonly found in cybersecurity datasets:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Brute Force attacks:} unauthorized access obtained through password-guessing techniques.
\item \textbf{Botnet attacks:} a collection of compromised devices controlled remotely, used to carry out DoS and DDoS attacks.
\item \textbf{DoS attacks:} temporary disruption of network services by flooding them with traffic, exhibiting sequential patterns [5].
\item \textbf{DDoS attacks:} server overload originating from multiple sources simultaneously; application-layer variants operate at low frequency.
\item \textbf{Infiltration attacks:} unauthorized network access obtained from within the perimeter [13].
\item \textbf{Probing attacks:} identification of network weaknesses through port scanning and IP address enumeration.
\item \textbf{Injection attacks:} insertion of malicious commands into a system, such as SQL injection or Cross-Site Scripting (XSS).
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Characterization of the CSE-CIC-IDS2018 Dataset }

The CSE-CIC-IDS2018 dataset substantially supersedes older benchmarks such as KDD99 and NSL-KDD, given the constant evolution of cyberattacks [3, 4]. Recent studies highlight its suitability for evaluating cloud environments and distributed architectures, owing to the diversity of attack scenarios it covers [19].
Network features are extracted at either the packet level (PCAP) or the flow level (NetFlow). The most relevant features include:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Source and destination ports:} used as flow keys.
\item \textbf{Flags:} particularly useful for detecting DoS and probing attacks.
\item \textbf{Connection duration:} a key indicator for identifying U2R and R2L attacks.
\item \textbf{Class imbalance:} benign traffic constitutes the majority class, while attack traffic represents the minority [14].
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Machine Learning: Random Forest (RF) }

The RF algorithm is frequently selected as a baseline model due to its high effectiveness in intrusion classification on complex datasets such as CSE-CIC-IDS-2017 and CSE-CIC-IDS2018 [2, 7].
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Foundations and Ensemble Learning (Bagging):} RF builds multiple decision trees using random subsets of the data; the final classification is obtained by majority voting, optimizing split criteria with metrics such as Gini impurity or Entropy [1, 7].
\item \textbf{Robustness and Overfitting Mitigation:} variance is reduced and overfitting avoided by averaging decorrelated trees and selecting random feature subsets at each split [1, 2].
\item \textbf{Hyperparameters:} number of estimators and maximum tree depth [7, 16].
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Deep Learning: Deep Neural Network (DNN)}

DNNs represent the complex model proposal in this study, justified by their capacity to automatically extract latent and hierarchical features [3, 5]. Recent research has combined DNNs with techniques such as LSTM or Autoencoders to improve detection accuracy on complex attacks [20].
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Architecture and 1D Adaptation:} a 1D DNN is implemented to process feature vectors as sequences, enabling the detection of local correlations [5, 6].
\item \textbf{Layers:} Convolutional, Pooling, Flatten, and Dense [4, 5].
\item \textbf{Activation Functions:} ReLU in hidden layers and Softmax at the output layer [6, 9].
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Preprocessing Techniques and Feature Engineering}

Preprocessing optimizes training time and preserves objectivity in model evaluation [5]. At large data volumes, normalization and encoding become necessary steps [6, 15]. Feature selection has also proven effective — it reduces noise introduced by high dimensionality and improves model generalization [7, 14].

\subsubsection{Cleaning and Data Encoding}

Removing inconsistent or null values is essential to avoid introducing bias into the model [8]. Encoding is equally necessary — it transforms categorical variables into numerical representations that learning algorithms can interpret [6].

\subsubsection{Class Balancing}

The CSE-CIC-IDS2018 dataset exhibits significant class imbalance, making a balancing technique necessary to control the large disparity between classes [6, 1]. Methods such as SMOTE and its variants (e.g., SMOTEBoost) are frequently applied to mitigate bias toward the majority class [16, 15].

\subsection{Evaluation Metrics}

\subsubsection{Accuracy}
El accuracy mide la proporción total de predicciones correctas.
\subsubsection{Recall}
Mide la capacidad del modelo para detectar todos los casos positivos reales.
\subsubsection{F1-score}
Es la media armónica entre precisión y recall.
\subsubsection{Curva de Roc}
Representa la tasa de verdaderos positivos frente a la tasa de falsos positivos.


