\subsection{Business Understanding}

The Business Understanding phase focuses on defining the project's objectives and requirements from both a cybersecurity and organizational value perspective. The primary goal is to build a robust system capable of detecting intrusions in computer networks to mitigate financial and operational risks. Given the rise in sophisticated attacks reported across the industry [6], there is a critical need for automated systems that reduce the burden on security analysts and minimize incident response time. Project success is defined by the model's ability to distinguish with high accuracy between benign and malicious traffic — minimizing false positives that could disrupt legitimate operations.

\subsection{Data Understanding}

This phase involves the collection and exploration of the CSE-CIC-IDS2018 dataset. The dataset was generated by the \textit{Communications Security Establishment} (CSE) and the \textit{Canadian Institute for Cybersecurity} (CIC) on AWS, simulating a real network with a diverse topology. It contains approximately 16 million records and covers seven distinct attack scenarios: Brute-force, Heartbleed, Botnet, DoS, DDoS, Web attacks, and Infiltration [3, 18].

Each record consists of 80 network flow features extracted with CICFlowMeter — including flow duration, packet statistics, and TCP flags. Initial data exploration reveals a strong class imbalance, where benign traffic significantly predominates over attack traffic. This is typical of real-world environments, but demands specific preprocessing strategies [8].

\subsection{Preprocessing}

Preprocessing was carried out in two phases: data cleaning and data transformation, following the workflow presented in Figure~\ref{fig:preprocesamiento}.

\begin{figure}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{Preprocessing.png}
\caption{Defined architecture for problem development} \label{fig1: arquitectura}
\end{figure}

Data cleaning began with the removal of inconsistent values. Outliers were identified — notably in the "flow duration" feature, which contained an extremely high negative value that hindered distribution analysis. All feature values were also enforced to be of numeric type.

After this cleaning stage, the dataset still exhibited severe class imbalance, so benign traffic records were randomly undersampled to match the total number of attack records and prevent training bias. This balancing step follows common practice in imbalanced intrusion-detection datasets [1, 18, 22, 23], while the prior cleaning stage addresses inconsistent or noisy values [8]. The final count yielded 4,341,486 records: 2,170,743 representing benign traffic and the remainder representing malicious traffic, resulting in an exact fifty-fifty split.

For data transformation, feature importance analysis was performed using the RF algorithm [10]. The dataset originally contains 79 features, excluding the target variable \texttt{Label}, so reducing this number to retain only the most representative features was necessary. Using Python's Scikit-learn library, a "RandomForestClassifier" was applied with 100 decision trees, a maximum depth of 10, and a random state of 42. The selected features are shown in Figure~\ref{fig:variablesSeleccionadas}.
Finally, due to the presence of very small minority classes, class grouping was applied — reducing the original 13 classes to 6 [22, 23].

