\subsection{Modeling}

The modeling phase is divided into two components: RF and DNN.

\subsubsection{Random Forest}
The RF model is notably resilient to class imbalance [11], making it a powerful tool to apply on the cleaned CSE-CIC-IDS2018 dataset. To ensure the evaluation reflects real performance and prevent data leakage, a stratified hold-out validation scheme was applied — partitioning the cleaned dataset into 70\% for training and 30\% for testing. Stratification was enforced to ensure that the proportion of minority classes remained identical across both sets.
Model construction followed two iterative stages:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Iteration 1:} A baseline model was trained using standard hyperparameters [24] and class weight balancing to focus training on minority classes. While it successfully detected most malicious traffic, it produced a very high false positive rate for the infiltration class.
\item \textbf{Iteration 2:} Hyperparameter optimization was performed on a 10\% data sample using "RandomizedSearchCV" with three-fold cross-validation, targeting maximum depth, number of decision trees, and split criteria. The resulting configuration was: 100 trees, maximum depth of 20, minimum 5 samples per split, and removal of forced class balancing.
\end{itemize}
Results for both experiments are reported in Table~\ref{tab:metricas_iteracion_1} and Table~\ref{tab:metricas_iteracion_2}.
\subsubsection{Deep Neural Network}
The DNN model achieved an overall accuracy of 86.32\% — lower than RF, but more precise on specific predictions. Per-class analysis shows the model meets its primary objective: full detection of attacks, including minority and complex classes.
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Iteration 1:} The DNN was trained on the cleaned and balanced data, requiring approximately one and a half hours of training time. The model reached 94\% precision on specific predictions; however, it failed to detect Web Attacks entirely, yielding a recall of 0\%. Despite the high overall index, this made the model ineffective in practice. Training used standard hyperparameters as the baseline configuration [25].
\item \textbf{Iteration 2:} The model was adjusted to explicitly prevent minority classes from being ignored. This intervention raised Web Attack detection to 96\%, representing a substantial improvement in the overall detection pipeline.
\end{itemize}
\subsection{Evaluation}
A general assessment of the results obtained across the different modeling iterations was conducted, comparing the performance of both approaches — RF and DNN — from both a technical standpoint and against the objectives defined at the project's outset.
Both models achieve strong performance, with overall accuracy above 86\%. RF delivered higher general accuracy and better balance across the most frequent classes. DNN, by applying class weights, achieved superior detection of underrepresented attack types — specifically Web Attacks and Infiltration — though at the cost of a lower global accuracy.

