\subsection{Best Result Obtained}

The best overall result was achieved by RF Iteration 2, reaching an accuracy of 94.55\%. Compared to DNN Iteration 2 (86.32\%), the RF model demonstrates higher general precision, reflecting a stronger ability to correctly classify the majority of instances. The optimized DNN, however, prioritizes minority class detection — particularly Web Attacks (recall 96\%) — at the cost of reduced global accuracy due to increased false positives.

\section{Discussion}

This work applied RF and DNN models to detect and classify potential intrusions in corporate networks using records from the CSE-CIC-IDS2018 dataset.
A distinguishing aspect of this study is the use of all malicious classes — not limited to DoS/DDoS variants — providing insight into RF behavior on classes such as Infiltration. Due to its high similarity with normal traffic, infiltration-type attacks are effectively camouflaged, an anomaly clearly visible in Figure~\ref{fig:matrizConfusion}.
The RF model's superior performance (94.55\%) over DNN (86.32\%) suggests that RF is more resilient to severe class imbalance, where malicious activity represents a minority relative to benign traffic. This aligns with the primary RF property highlighted in [11], where the main differentiation lies in the application of hybrid methods to further enhance detection capability.
The use of an RF classifier for feature selection and class grouping contrasts with several recent studies [11, 23, 10], with notable variations in this work — for instance, the number of trees used in the feature selection RF. While [10] employs 1,000 trees, this study explores a configuration of 100 trees.

\section{Conclusions}

Experiments conducted on the CSE-CIC-IDS2018 dataset demonstrate the superior effectiveness of the RF model over DNN, evaluated using standard classification metrics. This outcome is attributed to RF's inherent resilience in detecting minority classes.
The RF model yields promising results for intrusion detection based on network traffic data.

Future work will evaluate the models on other widely used datasets — CSE-CIC-IDS2017, InSDN, NSL-KDD, and UNSW-NB15 — and explore hybrid approaches to improve upon the results obtained here.

